=Poisson distribution: DNA mutations, radioactive decay, photons over time
discrete, number of events in time interval
λ = average number of events
probability of k events is (λ^k * e^-λ) / k!

=Causality: unidirectional cause-effect relationship between variable, cause is responsible for effect
=Correlation: relationship between random variables
Correlation coefficient: measure of correlation, 0 = no correlation, 1 = perfect correlation
Correlation does not imply causation: two variables can occur together due to third variable or coincidence
- Spurious correlation: correlation without causality
- e.g. ice cream sales and drownings (independently caused by hot weather)

Regression to mean: if sample of random variable is extreme, next sample will likely be closer to mean
Outlier: data point significantly different from other observations (e.g. Leonardo da Vinci)
- can indicate measurement error, fat-tailed distribution or novelty/anomaly
